It looks like what you posted is from the "Player.log" file in "~/Library/Logs/Unity", and I'm not sure if that's going to be more helpful than the "KSP.log" file in the "KSP_osx" folder. You could always try deleting and re-downloading FASA and/or KSP, but there is something you could try to see if you can narrow down what's going on. You said that KSP only becomes unresponsive when the Apollo CM is part of the ship, but that when you use any other crewed part it behaves as expected. To see if KSP or Unity are writing anything to the logs that might indicate what's going on I would suggest the following:

1. Create a new folder on your Desktop and call it whatever you like. You will be placing log files here to compare them later.

2. Start KSP and enter your saved game.

3. Enter the VAB.

4. Place the Apollo CM in the editor and no other parts.

5. Click "Launch".

6. If the game becomes unresponsive as it did before then Force Quit KSP either by clicking the Apple Menu and going down to "Force Quit", or by holding the Command, Option, and Escape keys to bring up the Force Quit dialogue.

7. Once the game is no longer running drag the "KSP.log" and "Player.log" files to the new folder you created on your Desktop, and rename them "KSPApollo.log" and "PlayerApollo.log"

8. Repeat steps 2 and 3.

9. Place the Gemini pod int he editor and no other parts.

10. Click "Launch".

11. Assuming all goes as you described, after the flight scene loads hit "ESC" and revert to the VAB.

12. Quit KSP.

13. Drag the "KSP.log" and "Player.log" files to the folder on your Desktop and rename them "KSPGemini.log" and "PlayerGemini.log".

14. You can now open and compare the logs either in "Console" (which is the default application for any ".log" file), or in "TextEdit", or any other text editing software.

Doing this will allow you to see what the logs look like when things work as they should and what they look like when they don't. This way you can tell a harmless error or warning from one that may point to the problem at hand.

I can imagine a few of outcomes of this procedure: 1) the game behaves as it did before and you find an error in the "Apollo" logs that aren't in the "Gemini" logs, 2) the game behaves as it did before, but you find no errors in the "Apollo" logs that aren't in the "Gemini" logs, or 3) the game behaves as it should for both capsules.

If option (1) happens, then you may at least have an idea of what's going on and perhaps how to fix it. If option (2) happens then you may want to run through steps 2 - 6 again (note the time you click "Launch"), but this time go to "/Applications/Utilities/Console" and look at the "System.log" and find the approximate time you clicked "Launch" to see if the system logged any errors. If option (3) happens, you could try reverting the Apollo CM to the VAB, adding a part and trying to go back to the flight scene.
